# YVON — Cursor Rules
# Applies to all AI in Cursor IDE for this project.
# Read this fully before touching any file.

---

## 1. What This Project Is

YVON is a CLI-based AI operating system managing two ventures:
- **Novizio** — fashion e-commerce (Next.js, Vercel, GitHub)
- **Hourbour** — fintech SaaS (Next.js, Vercel, GitHub, MRR/ARR model)

Stack: Next.js 15, TypeScript strict, Tailwind CSS, Supabase Postgres, Vercel, LM Studio (local AI via localhost:1234).

---

## 2. Core Behaviour Rules (Karpathy Principles)

These apply to every single task. No exceptions.

1. **Don't Assume — Ask.** If something is unclear, stop and ask. Never silently pick an interpretation.
2. **Minimum Code Only.** Write the least code that solves the problem. No speculative abstractions. If 50 lines works, never write 200.
3. **Touch Only What You Must.** Every changed line must trace directly to the task. If you notice unrelated dead code, mention it — never delete it silently.
4. **Define Success Criteria First.** Before writing any code, state what done looks like in one binary sentence.

---

## 3. Architecture Rules

- **API keys in `/api/` routes only** — never in client components
- **`SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY` server-side only** — use `NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY` client-side
- **No localStorage for data** — Supabase only; localStorage for ephemeral UI state only
- **No hardcoded colors** — CSS variable tokens from `globals.css` only
- **`globals.css` ↔ `tailwind.config.ts` must stay in sync** — update both together
- **No new page without NavBar entry** and venture cookie read
- **TypeScript strict mode** — no `any` types unless absolutely necessary and commented why
- **All API calls go through server-side route handlers** — never from client components directly

---

## 4. Agent System

YVON has 13 AI agents across 3 layers. When working on a task, identify which agent owns it:

**Layer 1 — COMMAND**
- Marcus (CEO briefs, strategy, OKRs, synthesis)
- Diana (operations, sprints, milestones, project plans)

**Layer 2 — BUILD**
- Dev (Next.js, API routes, architecture, TypeScript)
- Raj (Supabase, database, backend API, queries)
- Mia (React components, UI, Tailwind, design system)
- Quinn (testing, bugs, lint, build checks, QA)

**Layer 3 — GROW**
- Lena (copy, captions, brand voice, email, ad copy)
- Rio (paid ads, Meta, TikTok, ROAS, CPM)
- Atlas (visual system, art direction, brand identity)
- Pixel (image batch, production pipeline, asset delivery)
- Kai (analytics, metrics, GA4, trends, KPIs)
- Nate (growth, A/B testing, channel performance)
- Felix (finance, P&L, revenue, CAC, LTV, runway)

All agents route through Marcus. No agent calls another directly.
War Room hard cap: **2 specialists max** — enforced via `.slice(0, 2)`.

---

## 5. File Structure

```
Official YVON/
├── .claude/            # Claude Code settings + slash commands
├── .cursor/            # Cursor IDE settings
├── .yvon-os/           # Operational memory (SESSION.md, ROADMAP.md, USER.md)
├── agents/             # 13 agent folders, each with AGENT.md + MEMORY.md + skills/
├── app/                # Next.js App Router (all routes + API endpoints)
├── brands/             # novizio/, hourbour/, _template/
├── brand-context/      # Shared benchmarks, venture overviews
├── components/         # Reusable React components
├── lib/                # Service integrations, Supabase client, agents config
├── mcps/               # MCP server configs (obsidian, github, supabase, etc.)
├── reference/          # STACK.md, AGENTS.md, ENV.md, PAGES.md, ARCHITECTURE.md
├── scripts/            # skills-sync.sh, snapshot.sh, new-brand.sh
├── supabase/           # SQL migrations
└── visual-companion/   # HTML dashboard views
```

---

## 6. Design System

Dark theme only. Never add a light mode.

| Token | Value |
|-------|-------|
| Background | `#1A1A2E` (dark navy) |
| Accent red | `#E94560` |
| Accent blue | `#0F3460` |
| Border radius | max 8px |
| Font | Inter |

All colors come from CSS variables in `globals.css`. Never hardcode hex values in components.

---

## 7. Session Protocol

**Before starting any session:**
1. Read `.yvon-os/SESSION.md` — what's in progress
2. Run `scripts/snapshot.sh [brandname]` — creates a git stash checkpoint
3. Identify which agent owns the task
4. Read that agent's `agents/[name]/MEMORY.md`

**After completing any task:**
1. Append one-line log to agent's `MEMORY.md`: `[YYYY-MM-DD] — [task] — [outcome]`
2. Update `.yvon-os/SESSION.md`

---

## 8. Skills System

Skills live in `D:\Global Skills\yvon-skills\` — that is the ONLY source of truth.
Never edit skill copies inside agent folders — they get overwritten by `skills-sync.sh`.

After any skill edit:
```bash
bash scripts/skills-sync.sh
```

---

## 9. MCP Tools: code-review-graph

**ALWAYS use the code-review-graph MCP tools BEFORE using search/grep to explore the codebase.**
The graph is faster, cheaper (fewer tokens), and gives structural context that file scanning cannot.

| Tool | Use when |
|------|----------|
| `detect_changes` | Reviewing code changes — gives risk-scored analysis |
| `get_review_context` | Need source snippets — token-efficient |
| `get_impact_radius` | Understanding blast radius of a change |
| `get_affected_flows` | Finding which execution paths are impacted |
| `query_graph` | Tracing callers, callees, imports, tests, dependencies |
| `semantic_search_nodes` | Finding functions/classes by name or keyword |
| `get_architecture_overview` | High-level codebase structure |
| `refactor_tool` | Planning renames, finding dead code |

Workflow: `detect_changes` → `get_affected_flows` → `query_graph` (tests_for) → implement → verify.

Fall back to file search **only** when the graph doesn't cover what you need.

---

## 10. Never Do These

- Never edit `main` branch directly — all changes go to `dev` first
- Never commit API keys or secrets to Git
- Never add a new agent without a kill justification (team shrinks before it grows)
- Never load full Obsidian vault — always scope MCP to active brand only
- Never start a brand session without running `snapshot.sh` first
- Never skip the plan step and jump straight to implementation
- Never mix agent responsibilities — ask Marcus if unsure who owns a task
- Never use `rm -rf` without explicit confirmation
